In [[mathematics]], '''Ihara's lemma''', introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Ihara|year=1975|loc=lemma 3.2|authorlink=Yasutaka Ihara}} and named by {{harvtxt|Ribet|1984}}, states that the kernel of the sum of the two ''p''-degeneracy maps from ''J''<sub>0</sub>(''N'')√ó''J''<sub>0</sub>(''N'') to ''J''<sub>0</sub>(''Np'') is [[Eisenstein ideal|Eisenstein]] whenever the prime ''p'' does not divide ''N''. Here ''J''<sub>0</sub>(''N'') is the [[Jacobian variety|Jacobian]] of the compactification of the [[modular curve]] of Œì<sub>0</sub>(''N'').

